# app.connect_activate(build_ui);
# # // Run the application
# app.run();
# } If we now click on one button, the other button's label gets changed. But whoops! Did we forget about one annoyance of reference-counted systems? Yes we did: reference cycles . button_increase holds a strong reference to button_decrease and vice-versa. A strong reference keeps the referenced value from being deallocated. If this chain leads to a circle, none of the values in this cycle ever get deallocated. With weak references we can break this cycle, because they do not keep their value alive but instead provide a way to retrieve a strong reference if the value is still alive. Since we want our apps to free unneeded memory, we should use weak references for the buttons instead [2] . Filename: listings/gobject_memory_management/4/main.rs # use std::{cell::Cell, rc::Rc};
